00031  Description: This file contains the lexical analyzer for the Object
00032               Description Language. The lexical analyzer is created
00033               using Lex and modifications to the lexical analysis of
00034               ODL should be made by modifying the Lex input file and
00035               not the C-language version of the analyzer produced by
00036               Lex.
00037 
00038  Author:  Randy Davis, University of Colorado LASP
00039 
00040  Creation Date: 17 April 1990
00041  Last Modified: 18 May 1991
00042  
00043  History:
00044 
00045    Creation - This routine was introduced in Version 1 of the ODLC library.
00046 
00047    Version 2.0 - 30 August 1990 - R. Davis, U. of Colorado LASP
00048      a) Upgraded to ODL Version 2.  The biggest change is the support
00049         of groups.  Support for ODL Version 1 features not found in
00050         Version 2 -- like the range operator -- remain so that the
00051         lexical analyzer can handle older labels as well as new ones.
00052      b) Added support for ODL Version 0 date and time format. 
00053 
00054    Version 2.1 - 13 March 1991 - R. Davis, U. of Colorado LASP
00055      a) Changed to a more general way to turn tokens into 'value data'
00056         structures by converting from the older ODLxToken routines to
00057         ODLConvertX routines.  Processing of string tokens was moved into
00058         a new action routine named yyGetStringToken.
00059      b) Added recognition of two values that are often entered incorrectly
00060         by users: file names without quotation marks (which are turned into
00061         strings); and the symbol N/A (for Not Applicable, which is turned 
00062         into a quoted symbol).
00063      c) Saved comments so they can be attached as annotation to the ODL tree.
00064 
00065   Version 2.2 - 18 May 1991 - M. DeMore, Jet Propulsion Laboratory
00066     Removed ODL function prototypes which are now in include files.
00067     Added include file odlinter.h.
00068 
00069   Version 2.3 - 13 October 1991 - M. DeMore, Jet Propulsion Laboratory
00070      Removed code in yyGetStringToken which used to process '\t' and
00071      `\n`.  They are now transferred exactly as is to the output string
00072      and are handled by the output routines instead.  This was done to
00073      prevent the lexer from eating backslashes in DOS file names.

00359 /*****************************************************************************
00360 
00361   Routine: yyGetStringToken
00362  
00363   Description:  Get a text string token.  The opening delimiter (") was
00364                 recognized by the lexical analyzer before this routine
00365                 was called.  This routine will read in the remainder of
00366                 the string token up to the end delimiter and it will
00367                 reformat the text string as it goes into an ODL string
00368                 value.
00369  
00370   Input:  No arguments required.  The text of the string token is gotten
00371           using the lexical analyzer input function (yyinput).
00372            
00373   Output: The text string is placed in the lexical analyzer's token buffer
00374           (pointed to by yytext) and the token character count (yyleng) is
00375           set to reflect the string length.
00376  
00377   MDD - October 22, 1991
00378         Modified to use dynamic memory allocation routines rather than
00379         a static array.
00380 
00381 *****************************************************************************/
00382 
00383 char *yyGetStringToken ()
00384 {
00385   char    c;                       /* Current input character               */
00386   int     newline;                 /* New line flag:                        */
00387                                    /*   0 - Not at the start of a line      */
00388                                    /*  +1 - Newline found in input string   */
00389                                    /*  -1 - Newline placed in output string */
00390 
00391   newline = 1;
00392 
00393   ODLNewString();
00394   
00395   while ((c = yyinput()) != '"' && c != '\0')
00396    {
00397     switch (c)
00398      {
00399       case '\n':
00400 
00401        /* End of current line : get rid of any trailing blanks on the line */
00402        
00403        while (ODLPeekString (1) == ' ') ODLBackupString ();
00404 
00405        /* If the last non-blank character on the line is a '-', then this
00406           is a word hyphen and we can delete it. If it is an '&' then this
00407           indicates that all characters to the left are to be left intact,
00408           although we do delete the '&'.  Otherwise we add a blank to
00409           separate the last word on the current input line from the first
00410           word on the next input line. If there are two or more newlines
00411           in a row, then we retain the newlines to separate paragraphs */
00412    
00413        if (newline > 0)
00414        { 
00415            if (ODLPeekString (1) && 
00416                   !(ODLPeekString (1) == 'n' && ODLPeekString (2) == '\\'))
00417            {
00418               ODLStoreString ('\\');
00419               ODLStoreString ('n');
00420            }
00421            ODLStoreString ('\\');
00422            ODLStoreString ('n');
00423        }
00424        else if (newline < 0)
00425        {
00426           newline = 1;
00427        }
00428        else
00429        {
00430            newline = 1;
00431            if (ODLPeekString (1) == '-' || ODLPeekString (1) == '&')
00432            {
00433               ODLBackupString ();
00434            }
00435            else if (ODLPeekString (1) && 
00436                     !(ODLPeekString (1) == 'n' && ODLPeekString (2) == '\\'))
00437            {
00438               ODLStoreString (' ');
00439            }
00440        }
00441        break;
00442 
00443       case ' ':  case '\t':
00444 
00445        /* Ignore a blank or tab at the beginning of an input line; otherwise
00446           copy a blank character into the output string */
00447        
00448        if (newline == 0)
00449        {
00450          ODLStoreString (' ');
00451        }
00452        break;
00453 
00454       case '\\':
00455          ODLStoreString (c);
00456          ODLStoreString (yyinput ());
00457          if (ODLPeekString (1) == 'n' && ODLPeekString (2) == '\\')
00458             newline = -1;
00459          else if (ODLPeekString (1) && 
00460               !(ODLPeekString (1) == 't' && ODLPeekString (2) == '\\'))
00461             newline = 0;
00462          break;
00463 
00464       default:
00465 
00466        /* Copy the input character to the token buffer */
00467        ODLStoreString (c);
00468        newline = 0;
00469         
00470      } 
00471    }     
00472 
00473   /* Terminate the token buffer */
00474 
00475   return (ODLStoreString ('\0'));
00476 }

00481   Routine: yyGetComment
00482  
00483   Description:  Get a comment and either attach it to the ODL tree or
00484                 put it where other routines can get at it and do so.
00485  
00486   Input:  No arguments required.  The text and length of the comment
00487           come from the global variables yyinput and yyleng.
00488            
00489   Output: No output parameters.  The comment is copied and saved for
00490           later processing.
00491  
00492 *****************************************************************************/

00494 #include  <ctype.h>

00496 void yyGetComment ()
00497 {
00498   int   ib;                   /* Index to first character in comment text   */
00499   int   ie;                   /* Index to last character in comment text    */
00500   int   il;                   /* Count of characters in comment text        */
00501   char *string;               /* Pointer to space allocated for comment     */
00502 
00503 
00504 
00505   /* Skip over any whitespace prior to the start of the comment */
00506 
00507   ib = 0;
00508   ie = yyleng - 1;
00509 
00510   for ( ; ib <= ie && isspace (yytext[ib]) ; ib++);
00511 
00512   /* Skip over the slash and asterisk that introduce the comment */
00513 
00514   ib += 2;
00515 
00516   /* Skip backward over any white space or ending comment delimiter */
00517 
00518   for ( ; ib <= ie && isspace (yytext[ie]) ; ie--);
00519 
00520   if (ie > ib && yytext[ie] == '/')
00521     {
00522       if (yytext[ie-1] == '*')
00523         {
00524           ie -= 2;
00525         }
00526     }
00527 
00528   /* Eliminate any trailing whitespace */
00529 
00530   for ( ; ie >= ib && isspace (yytext[ie]); ie--);
00531 
00532   /* Get the number of characters in the comment string */
00533 
00534   yytext[ie+1] = '\0';
00535   il = (ie >= ib)? ie-ib+1 : 0;
00536 
00537   if (ODLcurrent_comment == NULL)
00538     {
00539       /* There is no comment currently.  Allocate space for a new
00540          comment and copy the text */
00541 
00542       string = (char *) malloc (il+1);
00543       if (string != NULL)
00544         {
00545           ODLcurrent_comment = strcpy (string, &yytext[ib]);
00546         }
00547     }
00548   else 
00549     {
00550       /* There is already some comment there: put in a newline character
00551          to end the previous comment line and append the current text
00552          to the comment */
00553 
00554       string = (char *) realloc (ODLcurrent_comment, 
00555                                  strlen (ODLcurrent_comment)+il+2);
00556       if (string != NULL)
00557         {
00558           strcat (string, "\n");
00559           ODLcurrent_comment = strcat (string, &yytext[ib]);
00560         }
00561     }
00562 
00563 return;
00564 }

00567 char *ODLStoreString (
00568 char c)
00569 {
00570    if (ODL_buffer != NULL)
00571    {
00572       if (ODL_buf_pos < ODL_buf_size)   
00573          *(ODL_buffer + ODL_buf_pos++) = c;
00574       else
00575       {
00576          ODL_buf_size = ODL_buf_size + ODL_BUFF_INCREMENT;
00577          ODL_buffer = (char *) realloc (ODL_buffer, ODL_buf_size); 
00578          if (ODL_buffer == NULL)
00579          {
00580             printf ("Out of memory for string storage.");
00581             exit (1);
00582          }
00583          *(ODL_buffer + ODL_buf_pos++) = c;
00584       }
00585    }

00601 char ODLBackupString ()
00602 {
00603    if (ODL_buf_pos > 0) 
00604    {
00605        ODL_buf_pos--;
00606        return (*(ODL_buffer + ODL_buf_pos));
00607    }
00608    else
00609       return (0);

00612 char ODLPeekString (
00613 int pos)
00614 {
00615    if (pos != 0 && ODL_buffer != NULL && pos <= ODL_buf_pos) 
00616       return (*(ODL_buffer + (ODL_buf_pos - pos)));
00617    else
00618       return (0);
00619 }

00621 void ODLKillString ()

00623    if (ODL_buffer != NULL) free (ODL_buffer);
00624    ODL_buffer = NULL;
00625    ODL_buf_pos = 0;
00626    ODL_buf_size = 0;
00627 }
